The following elements have produced this safe operating record:
Process hazard analysis and review, including corrective action follow-up requirements;
Standard operating procedures that all operators of the refrigeration system must follow;
Formal operator training;
Preventative maintenance to ensure that the entire refrigeration system is mechanically sound;
Procedures to ensure that changes to the refrigeration system are managed so ammonia flow
remains safe;
Safety review prior to the start-up of new or modified equipment;
Audits of the PSM and RMP programs;
Incident investigations to ensure that lessons are learned to prevent future incidents;
Employee involvement in risk reduction programs;
Contractor safety procedures are reviewed to ensure outside workers exercise the same safety
consciousness as employees;
A work permit system that ensures all welding work is conducted safely;
Process safety information; and
Emergency planning and response.

The brewery additionally complies with the requirements of the OSHA PSM standard (40 CFR
1910.119), the EPA RMP rules (40 CFR 68), and applicable Recognized and Generally Accepted
Refrigeration System Practices for Equipment, Design, and Installation of Ammonia Mechanical
Refrigerating Systems.

Five-Year Accident History
The brewery has had no releases that have caused onsite or offsite injuries, or damage to property or the environment. 

Emergency Response Program
The Merrimack brewery has in place a variety of emergency response procedures in the event of an incident involving ammonia. The emergency response program is based on OSHA's requirements for emergency action plans (29 CFR 1910.38) and HAZWOPER (29 CFR 1910.120). We have trained employees for emergency response and maintain a plan titled ES Incident Plan
(HAZWOPER Plan) which has been supplied to, and discussed with, Merrimack Fire Department. We conduct annual drills with local agencies to help us remain prepared to imple

l (Brewhouse Glycol Cooler) located outside the Brewhouse (Building 3) fails and releases 9246 pounds of anhydrous ammonia(5.42 lbs/gal @ 32 psig, 18.6 deg F).  There are administrative controls which limit the amount of ammonia in the receiver, so an 80% full level was used.  As the vessel is located outdoors, no mitigating measures apply when modeling using RMP*Comp.  Ammonia could travel 1.7 miles before dispersing enough to no longer pose a threat to the public.

This scenario is unlikely to occur at the Merrimack brewery for a number of reasons:
Brewery piping and vessels that contain ammonia meet or exceed industry manufacturing and
quality control standards;
Ammonia is not corrosive in the form in which it is used at the brewery;
Pressure relief safety valves limit operating pressures so the chance of a large-scale release is
minimal;
Operating level of the vessel is well below full capacity with routine monitoring and high level safety interlocks; 
Manual safety valves allow the immediate shut-off of the ammonia system;
Equipment is inspected and kept in proper working order and replaced when necessary;
The brewery has an emergency response plan and equipment in place (see description below).

Alternative Release Scenario
We have also identified an alternative release scenario involving the release of 1750 pounds of anhydrous ammonia due to the opening of a pressure safety relief valve, which itself is a system
safety device designed to relieve pressure to avoid a more serious release. This release scenario is based upon historical release data for Anheuser-Busch breweries. Under common weather
conditions, this amount of ammonia could travel 0.3 miles and remain mostly on brewery property before dispersing enough to no longer pose a threat to the public.

